{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475312"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:31:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:31:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12600"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12600"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.78,0.08,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48910"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5093"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33910"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1282"},{"type":"tags","id":"1866"},{"type":"tags","id":"4807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8523"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13361"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48910"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old child presents to the Emergency Department with her mother, reporting a high fever for the past four days. The fever is associated with cough and runny nose. A rash has also developed over the last two days. The child has not been vaccinated due to parental concerns about vaccine side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a temperature of 40\u00b0C, pulse rate 150/min, respiratory rate 22/min, and oxygen saturation 98% on room air. She has bilateral conjunctivitis. There is a maculopapular rash on her face and trunk. Her respiratory examination is normal. White patches are visible on the buccal mucosa. The pharynx is mildly inflamed, with no tonsillar enlargement. Otoscopic examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chickenpox","Measles","Scarlet fever","Rubella","Roseola infantum"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Emeasles\u003C/strong\u003E. The combination of high-grade fever, cough, coryza (runny nose), conjunctivitis, and maculopapular rash is characteristic of measles. The white patches on the buccal mucosa are likely Koplik spots, which are pathognomonic for measles. The patient\u0027s unvaccinated status further increases the likelihood of this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeasles is an acute, highly contagious viral disease caused by an RNA virus of the Paramyxoviridae family. It is transmitted by respiratory droplets. The disease is characterised by high-grade fever, cough, coryza, conjunctivitis, Koplik spots (bluish-white spots with surrounding erythema in buccal mucosa), and a maculopapular rash that extends from the head and spreads downwards. Diagnosis is usually clinical, and treatment is primarily supportive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChickenpox\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a low-grade fever, mild cough, and a characteristic rash in various stages of development, ranging from red macules and pustules to crusted scabbed vesicles. The rash of chickenpox is usually more vesicular and itchy compared to the maculopapular rash of measles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScarlet fever\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by high-grade fever followed by sore throat, strawberry tongue, and a red rash on the skin that feels like sandpaper. The absence of a sore throat and strawberry tongue makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERubella\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a low-grade fever, lymphadenopathy, and a rose-pink papular rash that begins on the face and neck, spreading to the trunk and extremities. The milder symptoms and different rash pattern make rubella less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERoseola infantum\u003C/strong\u003E causes a high fever for several days, followed by a rash that appears when the fever breaks. The rash in roseola typically starts on the trunk and then spreads to the limbs, whereas the measles rash spreads from the head downwards. The presence of respiratory symptoms and conjunctivitis also makes measles more likely than roseola.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Symptoms of measles include a high-grade fever, cough, coryza, conjunctivitis, Koplik spots (bluish-white spots with surrounding erythema in buccal mucosa) and a maculopapular rash that extends from the head and spreads downwards.","Measles is highly contagious and can be prevented through vaccination.","Diagnosis of measles is primarily clinical, based on characteristic symptoms and physical examination findings."],"references":["Kondamudi NP, Waymack JR. Measles. [Updated 2022 Oct 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448068/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33910"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12600"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33910","links":{"self":"ht